          <p class='first-para'>
            Before the noble Lord, Lord Bradshaw, decides what he will do with the amendment, I should like to ask my noble friend a couple of questions for clarification. He has argued long and hard that the Department for Transport does not need a strategy for the railways because it is a strategic authority. Which other parts of its responsibility in transport have strategies? We have discussed air, motorcycles and buses; I believe there was to be one of walking, but I cannot remember whether it was ever published. If we can have strategies on all those, why cannot we have one on the railway?</p><p>
            My noble friend said that when the Bill gets Royal Assent, the Strategic Rail Authority's strategies will be taken up by the transition grouping in the department. He did not say whether they would continue until the transition grouping had decided what to do with them.
