            Clause 4 is one of the smallest clauses in the Bill. It is perhaps one of the most contentious and could be one of the most objectionable. The reason is that it concerns the jurisdiction of the Office of the Rail Regulator rather than the independence of the regulatory authority.</p><p>
            Independence is all very well but what matters just as much is the jurisdiction of the authority&#x2014;what it actually does. The Secretary of State has insisted that the Office of the Rail Regulator will remain independent. We accept that; it is not an issue. Of course we know that, after the possibly unlawful decision of the previous Secretary of State to apply for Railtrack to be put into administration in October 2001&#x2014;and, indeed, the threats made to the previous rail regulator in relation to his independence&#x2014;the independence of the economic regulation of the railways is not now in dispute but, rather, its jurisdiction.</p><p>
            <a class='permalink column-permalink' id='column_48gc' title='Col. 48GC &mdash; HL Deb 28 February 2005 vol 670 c48GC' name='column_48gc' href='#column_48gc' rel='bookmark'>48GC</a>
